  "scopeAndContentNote": "In 1943, with China as a member of  of the allied nations in War World II, this act was proposed by Representative Warren G. Magnuson of the State of Washington, passed by Congress and signed by President Franklin D. Roosevelt on December 17, 1943.  The act repealed the discriminating exclusion acts against Chinese immigration that had been in place for over 60 years.  It allowed Chinese immigration into the United States, which had been ceased  with the passage of An Act to Execute Certain Treaty Stipulations Relating to Chinese (\"Chinese Exclusion Act\") of May 6, 1882 (NAID 575215), permitted some Chinese immigrants already residing in the country to become naturalized citizens and established an immigration quota for China of 105 visas per year.",
  "naId": 299853
}